<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-660-399  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 660 399.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Nov 26 1990 n618 p61(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Developers grapple with 32-bit software monster: as power curverises, so does complexity.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Weiss, Ray.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Increasing power of 32-bit computer systems means greater problemsfor software developers.andP;  No longer limited by small addressingranges or restricted local-memory size, software (which could bedescribed as collections of discrete, finite state machines) iscoming up hard against a complexity barrier born of a much greaternumber of states than hardware, and descriptive mathematicalfunctions that cannot be verified by traditional engineeringmathematics.andP;  This leads to a fundamental limitation to softwarereliability that worsens as programs grow larger.andP;  Portability isalso a major issue; to be successful, packages must run acrossmultiple hardware/software platforms, forcing developers tocontend with different processor architectures, graphicssubsystems and software environments.andP;  Other issues relate to thelack of standardization in low-level development tools and theincrease in complexity caused by combining implementationlanguages to derive the benefits of a higher level language.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     32-BitSoftware DesignSoftware ComplexitySoftware MigrationApplications.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   32-bit application world grows in complexity. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>